==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|forsaken||to reject, deny}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|forsacan||to dispute, quarrel, refuse, oppose}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*frasakaną||to renounce}}, equivalent to {{prefix|for|sake|lang=en}}. Akin to {{etyl|nl|-}} {{m|nl|verzaken}}, {{etyl|gmh|-}} {{m|gmh|versachen||to deny}}, {{etyl|da|-}} {{m|da|forsage||to give up}}, {{etyl|no|-}} {{m|no|forsake||to give up, renounce}}, {{etyl|sv|-}} {{m|sv|försaka||to give up, to be without}}, {{etyl|got|-}} {{m|got|𐍃𐌰𐌺𐌰𐌽||to rebuke, quarrel}}.<ref>{{R:Webster 1913|forsake}}</ref>

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/fɔɹˈseɪk/|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|eɪk|lang=en}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|forsakes|forsaking|forsook|forsaken}}

# To [[abandon]], to give up, to [[leave]] ''([[permanently]])'', to [[renounce]].

